ular silence of having given too much for too long."}]]}]]}]]}],["$","main",null,{"className":"max-w-[1440px] mx-auto px-5 md:px-12 relative z-[1]","children":[["$","section",null,{"className":"border-b border-line","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-3 text-[11px] tracking-[0.32em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold pt-10 pb-4","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block w-5 h-px bg-ink-faint"}],"Choose an emotion"]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-wrap gap-2 md:gap-3 pb-8","children":[["$","$L4","empty-achievement",{"href":"/burnout/empty-achievement","className":"text-[14px] md:text-[15px] font-semibold tracking-[-0.005em] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-full transition-all duration-300 no-underline bg-white/[0.06] text-ink-soft hover:text-ink hover:bg-white/[0.10] border border-white/[0.08]","children":"Empty Achievement"}],["$","$L4","compassion-fatigue",{"href":"/burnout/compassion-fatigue","className":"text-[14px] md:text-[15px] font-semibold tracking-[-0.005em] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-full transition-all duration-300 no-underline bg-accent text-bg shadow-[0_0_24px_rgba(19,237,255,0.35)]","children":"Compassion Fatigue"}]]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"border-b border-white/8 py-12 md:py-16","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-[720px]","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-5 flex items-center gap-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"h-px w-6 bg-accent/60"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-accent/70","children":["On ","Compassion Fatigue"]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-[16px] font-normal leading-[1.8] text-ink-soft md:text-[18px]","children":"You have been the strong one. The one who stayed. The one who showed up when everyone else found reasons not to. You held other people’s pain for so long it became indistinguishable from your own. And now something in you has gone quiet — not peaceful quiet, but numb quiet. You still care. You just cannot find the caring right now. These films understand the cost of sustained empathy. They do not shame the caregiver for reaching a limit. They witness the particular exhaustion of those who made their love a daily practice."}]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"py-16 md:py-20","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-end md:justify-between gap-6 mb-10 md:mb-14","children":[["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-3 mb-4 text-[11px] tracking-[0.32em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block w-5 h-px bg-ink-faint"}],"Compassion Fatigue"]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-[32px] md:text-[44px] lg:text-[56px] font-bold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.025em] text-ink max-w-[820px]","children":"Films for when there is nothing left to give."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"text-[12px] tracking-[0.18em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold md:text-right shrink-0","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"block text-[44px] md:text-[56px] text-ink font-bold tracking-[-0.03em] normal-case leading-none","children":"10"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-2 block","children":"Curated films"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"py-10 border-b border-white/6 mb-10","children":["$","$L5",null,{"films":[{"title":"Ordinary People","director":"Robert Redford","year":1980,"rating":8.9,"mood":"ash","story":"A family struggles to survive after a boating accident kills one son and leaves the other drowning in guilt — a film about the enormous effort of ordinary living after catastrophe.","why":"The exhaustion of being the survivor, the one who stayed, the one who must hold together what everyone else cannot face.","after":"You'll stop punishing yourself for being the one who lived.","direction":"Redford's controlled, precise direction lets the performances carry everything.","cinematography":"John Bailey photographs suburban Illinois 